- VSCode Version: 1.4
- OS Version: Mac OS X El Capitan

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Open a .php file that contains a class
2. Press `cmd + p`
3. Type `@`

You should see a list of symbols in the file at this point, but it doesn't seem to work for PHP files.  This is pretty crucial in order to switch from another editor to VS Code for PHP developers.

Here is a sample PHP class to test this with, make sure to save the file with a .php extension.

```
<?php

class Vegetable {

   var $edible;
   var $color;

   function Vegetable($edible, $color="green")
   {
       $this->edible = $edible;
       $this->color = $color;
   }

   function is_edible()
   {
       return $this->edible;
   }

   function what_color()
   {
       return $this->color;
   }

} // end of class Vegetable
```

I am lacking options how to setup a debugger for my programming language.

My language has a standalone runtime the developer should be able to place anywhere. I would like the user to set a configuration variable to point out where the runtime is.

Here's an example of such configuration (I will soon pump the whole code up into cheery/vscode-lever):

```
"configuration": {
  "type": "object",
  "title": "Lever tools configuration",
  "properties": {
    "lever.runtime_path": {
      "type": "string",
      "default": "c:\\lever",
      "description": "The folder path to the runtime this editor should use during debugging lever applications."
    }
  }
}
```

I've setup my debugger like this in package.json:

```
"debuggers": [
  {
    "type": "lever",
    "label": "Lever Debugger",
    "enableBreakpointsFor": {
      "languageIds": [
        "lever"
      ]
    },
    "program": "debug.js",
    "runtime": "node",
    "args": [],
    "variables": {
      "getLeverRuntimePath": "extension.getLeverRuntimePath"
    },
    "initialConfigurations": [
      {
        "name": "Lever-Run",
        "type": "lever",
        "request": "launch",
        "program": "${workspaceRoot}/main.lc",
        "lever_path": "${command.getLeverRuntimePath}",
        "stopOnEntry": false
      },
      {
        "name": "Lever-Debug",
        "type": "lever",
        "request": "launch",
        "program": "${workspaceRoot}/main.lc",
        "lever_path": "${command.getLeverRuntimePath}",
        "stopOnEntry": true
      }
    ],
    "configurationAttributes": {
      "program": {
        "type": "string",
        "description": "Workspace relative path to script to run",
        "default": "${workspaceRoot}/main.lc"
      },
      "stopOnEntry": {
        "type": "boolean",
        "description": "Automatically stop after launch.",
        "default": true
      },
      "lever_path": {
        "type": "string",
        "description": "Path to lever's configuration file",
        "default": "${command.getLeverRuntimePath}"
      }
    }
  }
],
```

The problems in this kind of configuration is that the user has to define "lever_path" -variable in their launch.json. I also get the runtime path only after the debugger has officially gone up. This means that I am unable to program my native runtime to fetch debug routine from lib/debugger.lc

Therefore I am forced to implement the debugging API via a node script. This problem prevents me from implementing debugging interfaces of the vscode within my language, and will prevent the spread of this debugging API.

I would prefer to get my config variable lever.runtime_path in environment variable, I tried to set it in extension.js with process.env.LEVER_PATH = vscode.workspace.getConfiguration("lever").get("runtime_path") without success.

(I am also unable to obtain a directory open dialog, so that I could assist the user to fill the configuration option when starting my tool, but I am not sure if that's a feature)

- VSCode Version: 1.4.0
- OS Version: OSX 10.11.6

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Install js-atom-grammar and Theme-TomorrowKit
2. type in:

```
export const loadedRecordsNumber = createSelector(
    [schemaSelector, recordsSelector],
    (schema, allRecords) => {
        const tableIds = Object.keys(allRecords);

        const nLoadedRecords = tableIds.reduce((num, tableId) => {
            const table = schema.tables[tableId];
            if (table && table.type === TYPE_MAIN) {
                return num + Object.keys(allRecords[tableId]).length;
            }
            return num;
        }, 0);

        return {
            nLoadedRecords,
        };
    }
);
```

